neovim. is there a plugin that retains information on the function name after you scroll it out of view? similar to the vscode feature? want lean mean fast config.

Absolutely. The feature you're looking for is widely known as "Sticky Scroll," and in the Neovim ecosystem, the gold standard for this is nvim-treesitter-context.

It uses Tree-sitter to understand the actual structure of your code (functions, loops, classes) rather than just regex, making it extremely accurate and "lean" since it hooks into the Tree-sitter parser you're likely already using.

The Plugin: nvim-treesitter-context
This plugin shows the context of the current visible lines at the top of your window. When you scroll a function signature out of view, it "sticks" to the top until you exit that function's scope.

🛠️ Installation (using lazy.nvim)
Since you want a "lean, mean" config, you can add it like this:

Lua
{
    "nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter-context",
    opts = {
        enable = true,            -- Enable this plugin (Can be enabled/disabled later via commands)
        max_lines = 3,            -- How many lines the window should span. Values <= 0 mean no limit.
        min_window_height = 0,    -- Minimum editor window height to enable context. Values <= 0 mean no limit.
        line_numbers = true,
        multiline_threshold = 20, -- Maximum number of lines to show for a single context
        trim_scope = 'outer',     -- Which context lines to discard if `max_lines` is exceeded. Choices: 'inner', 'outer'
        mode = 'cursor',          -- Line used to calculate context. Choices: 'cursor', 'topline'
    }
}
Why it fits your "Lean & Fast" requirement:
Performance: It is written in Lua and leverages Neovim's built-in Tree-sitter engine. It only updates when the cursor moves or the window scrolls, meaning zero idle CPU usage.

Visuals: It uses a floating window that matches your theme's colors automatically (specifically the TreesitterContext highlight group).

Interaction: You can jump to the "stuck" line by simply clicking it (if mouse is enabled) or using the command :TSContextToggle.

Pro-Tips for your Config:
Quick Jump: You can bind a key to jump to the context header (the function definition) currently stuck at the top:

Lua
vim.keymap.set("n", "[c", function()
  require("treesitter-context").go_to_context(vim.v.count1)
end, { silent = true })
Appearance: If the background of the sticky header looks weird, you can customize it in your init file:

Lua
vim.api.nvim_set_hl(0, "TreesitterContext", { bg = "#2c2e34" }) -- Set to a slightly different grey
Note: Make sure you have nvim-treesitter installed and the parsers for your specific languages (e.g., :TSInstall python) downloaded, as this plugin relies on them to "read" the function names.

this uses treesitter, not the lsp? would vscode use something more akin to the lsp?

Good observation. You’ve hit on the fundamental difference between how Neovim and VS Code handle code intelligence.

The short answer: Neovim uses Tree-sitter for this, while VS Code uses a hybrid approach that leans heavily on its own internal "Document Symbol" providers (which are often powered by LSP).

Here is the breakdown of why Neovim’s Tree-sitter approach is actually the "leaner, meaner" way to do it.

1. Tree-sitter (Neovim's Way)
Tree-sitter is a syntax parsing library. It builds a concrete syntax tree of your source file in real-time.
+1

How it works: It sees your code as a tree of nodes (e.g., function_declaration -> block -> if_statement). When you scroll, the plugin just looks "up" the tree from your current line to see which function or class node you are currently inside.

Speed: Instant. Because the tree is stored in memory and updated incrementally as you type, there is almost zero latency.

Reliability: It works even if your code doesn't compile or if the LSP hasn't finished indexing your 50,000-line project.

"Lean" factor: It only cares about the current file. It doesn't need to boot up a heavy background server (LSP) to know you're inside a function.

2. LSP (VS Code’s Way)
VS Code’s "Sticky Scroll" uses what they call Document Symbols.

How it works: VS Code asks a "Provider" (usually the Language Server) for a list of all symbols in the file and their ranges. When you scroll, VS Code checks your scroll position against those ranges.

The Hybrid Reality: While VS Code can use LSP, for common languages like TypeScript or HTML, it often uses its own built-in high-performance parsers (which are very similar to Tree-sitter) to keep the UI snappy.

Overhead: If a language doesn't have a native VS Code parser, it falls back to the LSP. This is why you might notice Sticky Scroll "lagging" behind in very large files in VS Code—it’s waiting for the Language Server to report back.

Comparison Table
Feature	nvim-treesitter-context	VS Code Sticky Scroll
Engine	Tree-sitter (Grammar-based)	Document Symbols (LSP or Built-in)
Speed	Extremely Fast (C-based parsing)	Fast (but depends on Provider speed)
Context	Strictly structural (Syntax)	Can be semantic (Symbol-based)
Resources	Low (Internal to Neovim)	Medium/High (Depends on the extension)
Offline/Broken Code	Works perfectly	Often breaks until code compiles/indexes
Why you want the Tree-sitter version:
In Neovim, using Tree-sitter for UI elements is preferred because it keeps the editor responsive. If your LSP hangs (which happens in big Rust or C++ projects), your UI won't freeze. The "context" will still be there because Tree-sitter is running locally in your Neovim process, not as a separate heavy server.

It is the definition of "lean"—it uses the same data Neovim is already using to highlight your code to also show you where you are.

can we further configure it to have an on-off toggle switch in case it's sometimes annoying?

Since nvim-treesitter-context provides a built-in command to toggle itself, setting this up is very straightforward. You can create a "toggle switch" using a single keybinding.

The "Lean" Toggle Setup
Add this to your init.lua. This uses a single key (like <leader>tc for Toggle Context) to flip the feature on and off instantly.

Lua
-- Toggle Sticky Scroll (Treesitter Context)
vim.keymap.set("n", "<leader>tc", ":TSContextToggle<CR>", { 
    silent = true, 
    desc = "Toggle Sticky Scroll" 
})
Making it "Meaner": Selective Disabling
Sometimes it's not the plugin that's annoying, but the specific file type. If you find it's great for Python but annoying for Markdown or Plain Text, you can automate the "off" switch in your config:

Lua
require'treesitter-context'.setup{
    -- ... your other config
    on_attach = function(buf)
        -- Disable for specific filetypes
        local ft = vim.bo[buf].filetype
        if ft == "markdown" or ft == "text" then
            return false -- Disable for these files
        end
        return true
    end,
}
Visual Polish (The "Annoyance" Fix)
Usually, people find Sticky Scroll annoying because it blends in too much with the code, making the top of the buffer look cluttered. You can make it look like a distinct "UI element" by giving it a specific background color:

Lua
-- Add this to your colorscheme settings
-- This gives the sticky header a slightly different background and a subtle underline
vim.api.nvim_set_hl(0, "TreesitterContext", { bg = "#282c34" }) 
vim.api.nvim_set_hl(0, "TreesitterContextBottom", { underline = true, sp = "Grey" })
Quick Summary of Commands
If you don't want to memorize a keymap right away, you can just type these into the command line:

:TSContextToggle — The master switch.

:TSContextEnable — Force it on.

:TSContextDisable — Force it off.

